<paragraph id="8B9F36F1FFC9DB2FC0EF5B2F5C27A0BA" blockId="2.[151,1436,1843,2012]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,933]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="344" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC0EF5B2F5C19A709" box="[151,273,1843,1868]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC0EF5B2F5C02A70E" bold="true" box="[151,266,1843,1868]" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
A species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC1C95B285F6AA70E" authorityName="Bleeker" authorityYear="1858" box="[433,610,1844,1868]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC1C95B285F6AA70E" box="[433,610,1844,1868]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">Lepidocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is readily distinguishable (
<figureCitation id="131B2A74FFC9DB2EC3B35B2F5918A70E" box="[971,1040,1843,1868]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1690,1712]" captionTargetBox="[153,1434,151,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-188@2.[153,1438,141,1673]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Species of Lepidocephalus. (A) L. nanensis, holotype, NIFI 4388, 72.0 mm SL, Nan River, Thailand; (B) L. macrochir, syntype, BMNH 1866.5.2.55, 77.7 mm SL, Sumatra or Java; (C) L. pallens, holotype, RMNH 7783, 41.9 mm SL; (D) L. pahangensis, holotype, ZRC 490, 35.8 mm SL; (E) L. spectrum, paratype, USNM 230267, 49.2 mm SL, Kalimantan. Photos A, C, D and E by Z. Randall; B by M. Sabaj Perez." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910405" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910405/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<tableCitation id="C6A2034AFFC9DB2EC4675B2F597AA70E" box="[1055,1138,1843,1868]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="9.[151,241,476,499]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 1. Characteristics that vary among species of Lepidocephalus. Measurements are in mm or percentages of standard length (SL). Range is followed by average in parentheses." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5F6679FFC2DB25C0EF5DC05E6AA251" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" tableUuid="DF5F6679FFC2DB25C0EF5DC05E6AA251">Table 1</tableCitation>
) from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC4BE5B285844A709" authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1989" box="[1222,1356,1844,1867]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spectrum">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC4BE5B285844A709" box="[1222,1356,1844,1867]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">L. spectrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of eyes and dark pigment on the body, and absence of tubules along the lateral line; from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC48A5B445894A72D" authority="van Hasselt, 1823" authorityName=", de Beaufort" authorityYear="1933" box="[1266,1436,1879,1903]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Acanthophthalmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pahangensis">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC48A5B445894A72D" box="[1266,1436,1879,1903]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">L. pahangensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of scales on top of the head; from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC2B75B605E36A7D6" authorityName="Vaillant" authorityYear="1902" box="[719,830,1916,1940]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallens">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC2B75B605E36A7D6" box="[719,830,1916,1940]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">L. pallens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the dorsal-fin origin well behind (vs. over) the pelvic-fin origin (predorsal length 65.0–69.3 vs. 59.9% SL); and from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC3955BBC5967A7F5" authorityName="Deein &amp; Tangjitjaroen &amp; Page" authorityYear="2014" box="[1005,1135,1952,1975]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanensis">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC3955BBC5967A7F5" box="[1005,1135,1952,1975]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">L. nanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a shorter snout (3.9–5.1 vs. 5.6–7.4% SL; 23.3–27.1 vs. 28.6–38.1% HL). 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2EC32F5BD85981A79E" baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[855,1161,1988,2012]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrochir">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2EC32F5BD85981A79E" box="[855,1161,1988,2012]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">Lepidocephalus macrochir</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC9DB2FC5FD5BD85C2BA0F2" authority="van Hasselt, 1823" authorityName=", de Beaufort" authorityYear="1933" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Acanthophthalmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="344" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="343" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pahangensis">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC9DB2FC5FD5BD85C2BA0F2" italics="true" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="344" pageId="2" pageNumber="343">L. pahangensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having 8 (vs. 9) branched dorsal-fin rays and 5–6 (vs. 4) branched anal-fin rays, and from 
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC5FD5C855CABA096" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC5FD5C855DE3A096" authorityName="Vaillant" authorityYear="1902" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallens">L. pallens</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC08F5CA15CABA096" authority="van Hasselt, 1823" authorityName=", de Beaufort" authorityYear="1933" box="[247,419,188,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Acanthophthalmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pahangensis">L. pahangensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC1A45CA15F6BA096" authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1989" box="[476,611,189,212]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spectrum">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC1A45CA15F6BA096" box="[476,611,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">L. spectrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a shorter head (16.6–18.8 vs. 23.2, 21.8, and 21.3–23.2% SL, respectively).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33A657AFFC8DB2FC0BF5D185E8FA28F" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9F36F1FFC8DB2FC0BF5D185851A127" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5D185C50A159" box="[199,344,260,285]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5D185C59A15F" bold="true" box="[199,337,260,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Description</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Body deep, slab-sided; greatest depth 15.7–18.9% SL. Head narrow, length 16.6–18.8% SL. Eye small, in dorsal half of head in shallow depression above bifid suborbital spine. Origin of dorsal fin behind origin of pelvic fin. Small axillary lobe on pelvic fin; small fleshy lobe at origin of pectoral fin. Pectoral fin falcate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F36F1FFC8DB2FC0BF5D735FACA21D" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Scales on top of head, cheek and opercle; body completely covered with minute, often deeply embedded scales. Lateral line complete, 105–150 pores; no tubules on lateral line. Mouth horseshoe-shaped; upper lip without median indentation; lower lip with median indentation on lower edge. Two pairs of rostral barbels; inner pair reaching to corner of mouth, outer pair slightly longer and reaching slightly past corner of mouth; one pair of maxillary barbels, reaching approximately to vertical at posterior end of groove containing suborbital spine. Large flap on anterior nostril. Dorsal rays iii,8; pectoral rays 10–11; pelvic rays 6–8; anal rays ii,5–6; upper branched caudal rays 7–8; lower branched caudal rays 7.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F36F1FFC8DB2FC0BF5E705E8FA28F" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5E705C47A2C1" box="[199,335,620,645]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5E705C40A2C7" bold="true" box="[199,328,620,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Coloration</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Described by Bleeker (1854) as “&quot;colore corpore pinnisque fuscescente-aurantiaco vel fusco; maculis vel vittis corpore pinnisque nullis,” which translates to: body and fins brown-orange or brown tinged with grayish-black; lacking spots or bands on body and fins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33A657AFFC8DB2FC0BF5ECB589CA3E1" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9F36F1FFC8DB2FC0BF5ECB589CA3E1" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5ECB5C68A2AD" box="[199,352,727,752]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC0BF5ECB5C51A2B2" bold="true" box="[199,345,727,752]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Distribution</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC1165EC45FAAA2B2" baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[366,674,728,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrochir">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC1165EC45FAAA2B2" box="[366,674,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Lepidocephalus macrochir</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is poorly represented in collections and known only from the Lamatang and Enim rivers in eastern Sumatra, the Pepeh River in central Java, and the Barito River basin in southern Borneo (
<figureCitation id="131B2A74FFC8DB2FC1115F035CBBA37A" box="[361,435,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,249,1699,1721]" captionTargetBox="[153,1429,349,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-196@4.[151,1436,339,1677]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of specimens of Lepidocephalus examined." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4910407" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4910407/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Previous reports of the distribution that included peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F3377661FFC8DB2FC4E75F03580EA37A" box="[1183,1286,799,824]" name="Malaysia" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and western Borneo (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B00FFC8DB2FC14F5F585CD1A31F" author="Roberts, T. R." box="[311,473,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" pagination="1 - 210" refId="ref8105" refString="Roberts, T. R. (1989) The freshwater fishes of western Borneo (Kalimantan Barat, Indonesia). Memoirs of the California Academy of Sciences, 14, 1 - 210." type="journal article" year="1989">Roberts, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) were based on the 
<typeStatus id="549B8853FFC8DB2FC2B35F585E30A31F" box="[715,824,836,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">holotypes</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC31C5F595910A31E" box="[868,1048,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC31C5F59591CA31E" authority="van Hasselt, 1823" authorityName=", de Beaufort" authorityYear="1933" box="[868,1044,836,860]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Acanthophthalmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pahangensis">L. pahangensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC42D5F5959CFA31E" authorityName="Vaillant" authorityYear="1902" box="[1109,1223,836,860]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallens">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC42D5F5959CFA31E" box="[1109,1223,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">L. pallens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, respectively. The occurrence of 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D72FFC8DB2FC1475F755CDDA3C2" baseAuthorityName="Bleeker" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[319,469,872,896]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cobitidae" genus="Lepidocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrochir">
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC1475F755CDDA3C2" box="[319,469,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">L. macrochir</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Barito River basin in southern Borneo and the Pepeh River in central Java supports the hypothesis of 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B00FFC8DB2FC1BB5F905FB3A3E7" author="de Bruyn, M. &amp; Ruber, L. &amp; Nylinder, S. &amp; Stelbrink, B. &amp; Lovejoy, N. R. &amp; Lavoue, S. &amp; Tan, H. H. &amp; Nugroho, E. &amp; Wowor, D. &amp; Ng, P. K. L. &amp; Siti Azizah, M. N. &amp; von Rintelen, T. &amp; Hall, R. &amp; Carvalho, G. R." box="[451,699,908,933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="344" pagination="398 - 410" refId="ref7561" refString="de Bruyn, M., Ruber, L., Nylinder, S., Stelbrink, B., Lovejoy, N. R., Lavoue, S., Tan, H. H., Nugroho, E., Wowor, D., Ng, P. K. L., Siti Azizah, M. N., von Rintelen, T., Hall, R. &amp; Carvalho, G. R. (2013) Paleo-drainage basin connectivity predicts evolutionary relationships across three southeast Asian biodiversity hotspots. Systematic Biology, 62 (3), 398 - 410." type="journal article" year="2013">
de Bruyn 
<emphasis id="B954EAE3FFC8DB2FC2495F915F6AA3E6" box="[561,610,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="344">et al</emphasis>
. (2013)
</bibRefCitation>
of a paleo East Sunda River basin connecting these land masses.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
